                                                "id":  "2-3-2",
                                                "title":  "Costing Two Benefit Plan Options",
                                                "duration":  "12 min",
                                                "xp":  150,
                                                "type":  "lesson",
                                                "body":  [
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "intro",
                                                                 "v":  "Choosing between competing benefit plan options almost always comes down to a side-by-side cost comparison. This exercise builds one from scratch."
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "box",
                                                                 "label":  "Option A: Standard Health Plan",
                                                                 "v":  "Premium per enrolled employee: $4,800/year\nEligible headcount: 280\nAssumed take-up rate: 72%\nEmployer pays: 80% of premium, employee pays 20%"
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "h",
                                                                 "v":  "Calculate Option A\u0027s Employer Cost Yourself"
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "p",
                                                                 "v":  "Calculate the total annual employer-paid cost for Option A, accounting for both the assumed take-up rate and the employer\u0027s 80% premium share."
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "reveal",
                                                                 "label":  "Reveal the calculation",
                                                                 "v":  "Enrolled employees = 280 × 0.72 = 201.6, round to 202.\u003cbr\u003eTotal premium cost = 202 × $4,800 = $969,600.\u003cbr\u003eEmployer share (80%) = $969,600 × 0.80 = $775,680.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOption A annual employer cost ≈ $775,680.\u003c/strong\u003e"
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "box",
                                                                 "label":  "Option B: Enhanced Health Plan",
                                                                 "v":  "Premium per enrolled employee: $5,900/year (richer coverage, drives higher take-up)\nEligible headcount: 280\nAssumed take-up rate: 84% (richer plan typically drives stronger enrolment)\nEmployer pays: 75% of premium, employee pays 25%"
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "p",
                                                                 "v":  "Calculate Option B\u0027s total annual employer-paid cost using the same method, then compare the two options\u0027 total employer cost."
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "reveal",
                                                                 "label":  "Reveal the calculation",
                                                                 "v":  "Enrolled employees = 280 × 0.84 = 235.2, round to 235.\u003cbr\u003eTotal premium cost = 235 × $5,900 = $1,386,500.\u003cbr\u003eEmployer share (75%) = $1,386,500 × 0.75 = $1,039,875.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOption B annual employer cost ≈ $1,039,875.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOption B costs the employer roughly $264,195 more per year than Option A — a 34% increase — driven by both the richer premium and the higher assumed take-up. This is the real number that should anchor any decision between the two options, not a surface-level comparison of premium prices alone, which would have understated the true cost gap since Option B\u0027s higher take-up compounds with its higher premium."
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "h",
                                                                 "v":  "Why the Decision Isn\u0027t Purely About the Cost Gap"
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "p",
                                                                 "v":  "A $264,195 cost difference only tells you what the upgrade costs — it doesn\u0027t tell you whether it\u0027s worth it. That requires weighing the cost gap against what Module 1 of the Total Rewards Foundations course covers: workforce preference data, competitive positioning, and the retention or attraction value the richer plan is expected to generate. A cost model answers \u0027what would this cost\u0027; it doesn\u0027t, by itself, answer \u0027should we do it.\u0027"
                                                             },
                                                             {
                                                                 "t":  "takeaways",
                                                                 "items":  [
                                                                               "Employer benefit cost depends on enrolled headcount (after applying take-up rate), the unit premium, and the employer\u0027s cost-share percentage.",
                                                                               "A richer plan\u0027s cost increase compounds two effects — a higher premium and typically higher take-up — which a surface-level premium comparison alone would understate.",
                                                                               "A cost model tells you what an option costs; deciding whether it\u0027s worth that cost requires separate workforce and strategic context.",
                                                                               "Comparing total employer cost, not unit premium price, is the only fair basis for choosing between two benefit plan options."
                                                                           ]
                                                             }
                                                         ]
